You are debugging a production issue where a high-throughput microservice periodically crashes with a `ConcurrentModificationException` under heavy traffic. A team member implemented a custom thread-safe LRU cache using the following code snippet:

java
@Service
public class CustomCacheService<K, V> {
    private final Map<K, V> cache = new LinkedHashMap<>(16, 0.75f, true) {
        @Override
        protected boolean removeEldestEntry(Map.Entry<K, V> eldest) {
            return size() > 500;
        }
    };

    public synchronized V get(K key) {
        return cache.get(key);
    }

    public synchronized void put(K key, V value) {
        cache.put(key, value);
    }

    public Collection<V> getValues() {
        return cache.values();
    }
}


Other services regularly call `getValues()` to inspect active cache contents.

You are debugging a production issue where database write operations occasionally fail silently, leading to data inconsistency. You locate a Spring `@Service` bean managing task execution. Under high concurrency, worker threads poll a custom queue-backed buffer and invoke a transactional method. However, you notice that the transactions do not roll back on runtime failures. The relevant snippet of the service is structured as follows:

java
@Service
public class TaskProcessorService {

    public void processPendingBuffer() {
        List<Task> tasks = drainBuffer();
        for (Task task : tasks) {
            executeTask(task);
        }
    }

    @Transactional(propagation = Propagation.REQUIRES_NEW)
    public void executeTask(Task task) {
        // DB operations here
        if (task.hasError()) {
            throw new TaskProcessingException("Failed to process task");
        }
    }
}
